  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>A Technical Proposal is Not a Technical Document</h3>
    <p>It’s natural for technical professionals to treat proposals like reports—dense with detail, rigor, and precision. But a proposal isn’t just a technical document. It’s a persuasive tool.<br><br>
Its purpose is to help the client say yes—with confidence.<br><br>
That means going beyond specifications to demonstrate your understanding of the project’s goals, risks, stakeholders, and broader context. Strong proposals don’t just explain what you’ll build. They show how you’ll adapt to change, manage competing priorities, and lead the one variable no model can predict: people.
</p>
  </div>

  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>A Discipline All Its Own</h3>
    <p>Every proposal is a project—complete with a schedule, scope, deliverables, and deadlines. It deserves the same structure, clarity, and care.<br><br>
Not all firms have dedicated proposal staff, but every team benefits from treating proposal management as a discipline in its own right. When roles are clear and coordination is strong, the process gains focus and momentum—especially in fast-moving, high-stakes pursuits.<br><br>
Twennie fills a critical gap with tools and strategies built specifically for managing proposals in technical environments—where precision matters, and time is always tight.
</p>
  </div>

  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>The Non-Technical Professional in a Technical World</h3>
    <p>Proposal managers often come from non-technical backgrounds. They bring critical skills that technical teams rely on: coordination, communication, persuasive writing, and business insight.<br><br>
Their success depends on influence, not authority. They’re expected to lead across disciplines, align stakeholders, and drive momentum—often without formal control.<br><br>
Twennie supports these professionals with tools and guidance tailored to the realities of technical environments—helping them thrive in their roles, and helping technical teams recognize the value they bring.
</p>
  </div>

  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>Managing a Portfolio of Proposals</h3>
    <p>Winning work through proposals is never guaranteed—but it shouldn’t feel like guesswork. Many firms submit multiple proposals before landing a win. That reflects not just competition, but often a lack of insight into what’s working and what isn’t.<br><br>
Proposal writing is one of the most expensive business development activities. Treating it as a repeatable, trackable discipline—not just a last-minute scramble—can make a real difference.<br><br>
Twennie helps teams move beyond trial and error with tools and strategies to evaluate performance, identify patterns, and refine their approach across the entire portfolio.
</p>
  </div>

  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>Defining Value Through the Client’s Eyes</h3>
    <p>Great proposals start with a simple but powerful question: What does the client truly value?<br><br>
It’s not just about meeting the RFP requirements. That’s the baseline. Clients make decisions above that line—where trust, excitement, and confidence come into play.<br><br>
What sets your proposal apart? What makes your approach feel like a better fit? What gives the client reason to believe you understand their world?<br><br>
Twennie helps teams shift perspective—from just qualifying for the work to clearly showing how their approach delivers unique, client-centered value.
</p>
  </div>

  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>The Tailored Proposal</h3>
    <p>No two clients are the same—and no two proposals should be either. Reusing language and templates may save time, but true differentiation comes from understanding what matters most to each client.<br><br>
If they’ve spent months planning their project, they deserve a proposal that reflects that investment—one that feels considered, relevant, and specific.<br><br>
Twennie helps professionals develop the insight and creativity needed to craft proposals that resonate, build trust, and rise above the competition.
</p>
